# Introducing ArkType 2.1: The first pattern matcher to bring the power of type syntax to JS
created: 2025-02-27, last updated: 2025-09-05, [Read more](https://www.reddit.com/r/javascript/comments/1izl7bg/introducing_arktype_21_the_first_pattern_matcher/)

```ts
import { match } from "arktype"; const processInput = match({
string: value => value.trim(),
number: value => value.toFixed(2),
boolean: value => value ?
"Yes" : "No",
default: () => "Unsupported input"
}); console.log(processInput("   hello "));
// ?^ "hello"
console.log(processInput(123.456));
// ? 123.46
console.log(processInput(true));
// ? "Yes"
...
So I will also share the TypeScript version of this which is also not going to use | .
This is because the concept of a discriminated union does not refer to the use of a union character.
It is referring to the concept of a set that can hold values of different and specific types.
Each value in the union is associated with a discriminant tag that indicates its specific type.
In a discriminated union, only one value is present at any given time, and the tag helps identify which type the current value belongs to.
This will throw an error, but we really have just created objects with a static value (the strings A and B ).

# ArkType: The Parse-Don't-Validate Sequel I Didn't Know I Needed
created: 2026-04-09, last updated: 2026-06-12, [Read more](https://cekrem.github.io/posts/arktype-parse-dont-validate-sequel/)

const out = User(rawData);
if (out instanceof type.errors) {
console.error(out.summary);
...
// "age must be at most 150 (was 200)"
return;
}
...
out.name;
...
A discriminated union says “this value is one of two things” in the type itself.
...
In Zod, if you want efficient union parsing, you have to explicitly tell it which field to discriminate on:
```
// Zod: you do the work
z.discriminatedUnion("type", [
z.object({ type: z.literal("email"), address: z.string() }),
z.object({ type: z.literal("sms"), phone: z.string() }),
]);
```
ArkType figures it out:
```
// ArkType: it figures it out
const Contact = type.or(
{ type: "'email'", address: "string" },
{ type: "'sms'", phone: "string" }
);
```
It automatically finds the most efficient discriminant, even across nested paths.
ArkType’s docs describe this as “set-theoretic,” which tracks.
The library represents types as sets and reasons about their relationships mathematically.

